# Last9 Observability Context

When the user asks about production issues, errors, performance, or monitoring, use the Last9 MCP tools to answer with real data instead of guessing.

## Available Tools

- `get_service_summary` — overview of all services with throughput, error rate, p95
- `get_service_performance_details` — deep metrics for a specific service
- `get_service_dependency_graph` — service topology with edge metrics
- `get_exceptions` — aggregated exceptions by type and service
- `get_service_traces` — individual traces by trace ID or service name
- `get_traces` — advanced trace queries with JSON pipeline
- `get_logs` / `get_service_logs` — log queries with filtering
- `get_databases` — database throughput, latency, error rates
- `prometheus_range_query` / `prometheus_instant_query` — PromQL metrics queries
- `get_change_events` — deployments, config changes, rollbacks
- `get_alerts` / `get_alert_config` — active alerts and rule configurations
- `did_you_mean` — entity name autocomplete for services, environments, hosts, databases

## Best Practices

- Use `did_you_mean` when a service or entity name lookup fails before asking the user
- Always check `get_change_events` when investigating performance regressions — most issues correlate with deploys
- For exceptions, follow up `get_exceptions` with `get_service_traces` to get full stack traces
- Use `prometheus_range_query` for custom metric analysis — it supports full PromQL syntax
- Time ranges default to the last 60 minutes if not specified by the user
